Phase 1: Investigation and Financial Analysis
Investigation Phase
Upon enrollment and execution of the Client Services Agreement, Republic Tax Relief will begin
to establish our position and relationship between you and the IRS as well with any other State
Taxing Authorities if necessary. This will include obtaining information on all outstanding returns,
what information the Tax Agent is requesting, and if any substitute returns have been force filed.
The first crucial steps to begin the process are listed below.
File Power of Attorney (IRS Form 2848)
Request a “stay of enforcement” with an IRS Collections division
representative in an attempt to defend against Enforced Collection Activity, if
needed.
Order all records of account, transcripts and income information on file with
the IRS; immediately after, we will contact the IRS’s Practitioners’ Priority
Service and receive an oral explanation of the IRS coding and classifications
for your overall taxpayer profile.
Personal Financial Analysis
Once we have received your completed Power of Attorney and Client Services Agreement, you
will receive a Personal Financial Questionnaire, which is necessary to provide us with a clear
understanding of your financial situation. In conjunction with the Personal Financial
Questionnaire and our communications with the IRS and State Taxing Authorities, we will
create
a Tax Resolution Program specific to your needs.
Completion of Investigation Phase
After we have conducted the Investigation and Financial Analysis, we will have identified the
various IRS resolution programs available specific to your situation. During your final
investigation consultation, we go through the details of your Personal Tax Resolution plan and
explain why we recommend this course of action. At this point, we will also provide you a
breakdown of costs to implement your Tax Resolution plan and an estimated timeframe to
complete your plan.
Average Time Frame: 30 Day
Phase 2: Final Resolution Proposal
Summary
Per our initial conversation, you owe approximately in back taxes. We discussed
several options for final resolution of your tax liabilities, and below is a description of the
programs that may be available once we have obtained your results of our investigation and
analysis. No fees will be incurred for implementation of a resolution strategy as described below
until after your IRS Investigation and Financial Analysis are completed and you have received a
Final Investigation Consultation.
POSSIBLE RESOLUTION OPTIONS
Individual results will vary depending on the results of our investigation. We make no
guarantees that these options will apply to your situation and these options listed are meant
strictly for explanation purposes only.
Offer in Compromise (OIC)
This program allows taxpayers to settle their entire tax debt for a lower amount based entirely
on what they can afford to pay. It requires full disclosure of all household income and expenses
and an analysis of net equity in assets.
{{DEBT}}
2
An OIC for an individual taxpayer typically takes one month to prepare and six months for the
IRS to process and accept. An OIC for a self-employed or corporate taxpayer typically takes
about two months to prepare and anywhere from nine months to over a year for the IRS to
process. Although these time frames are subject to change based on the time of year and IRS
staffing. Very few of these are accepted by the IRS relative to those who apply. This is a rarely
accepted option and requires special circumstances.
Average Time Frame: 9-12 months
Installment Agreement (IA)
This program works in two ways. If it is a Hardship Payment Installment Agreement, taxpayers
can pay less than what they owe over time and the remaining debt will expire (unlike the OIC
program, where taxpayers typically pay what they can afford to pay all at once). The monthly
payment is calculated based upon what they can afford to pay each month.
A Full Payment Installment Agreement is an agreement between the taxpayer and the IRS to
pay the debt in full, over the length of time the IRS can legally collect the debt (typically 10
years) or less, depending on the agreement. In order to reduce your debt with any form of
Installment Agreement program, we can submit a Penalty Abatement Petition with the IRS
Appeals Division once we have established compliance.
Average Time Frame: 1-6 months
Currently Non Collectible (CNC)
Currently Non-Collectible (CNC) status is a determination by IRS Collections personnel to
suspend collections due to economic hardship. The IRS agrees to suspend collections (i.e.,
refrain from issuing a wage or bank
levy) so long as the taxpayer's income remains at the same
level as when CNC status was approved and the taxpayer files and pays taxes on time each
year.
Average Time Frame: 3-6 months

THE AWARD RENDERED BY THE ARBITRATOR SHALL BE FINAL AND SHALL NOT BE SUBJECT TO
VACATION OR MODIFICATION. JUDGMENT ON THE AWARD MADE BY THE ARBITRATOR MAY BE
ENTERED IN ANY COURT HAVING JURISDICTION OVER THE PARTIES. IF EITHER PARTY FAILS TO
COMPLY WITH THE ARBITRATOR'S AWARD, THE INJURED PARTY MAY PETITION THE CIRCUIT COURT
FOR ENFORCEMENT. THE PARTIES AGREE THAT THE ARBITRATOR MAY NOT CONSOLIDATE
PROCEEDINGS OF MORE THAN ONE PERSON'S CLAIMS, AND MAY NOT OTHERWISE PRESIDE OVER
ANY FORM OF REPRESENTATIVE OR CLASS PROCEEDINGS. THE PARTIES SHALL SHARE THE COSTS
OF ARBITRATION INCLUDING, ATTORNEY'S FEES, EQUALLY. IF THE CONSUMER'S SHARE OF THE
COST IS GREATER THAN $3,000 (THREE THOUSAND DOLLARS), RTR WILL PAY THE CONSUMERS
SHARE OF COSTS IN EXCESS OF THAT AMOUNT. IN THE EVENT A PARTY FAILS TO PROCEED WITH
ARBITRATION, UNSUCCESSFULLY CHALLENGES THE ARBITRATOR'S AWARD, THE OTHER PARTY IS
ENTITLED TO COSTS OF SUIT, INCLUDING REASONABLE ATTORNEY'S FEE FOR HAVING TO COMPEL
ARBITRATION OR DEFEND OR ENFORCE THE AWARD.

Part II Declaration of Representative
Under penalties of perjury, by my signature below I declare that:
•
I am not currently suspended or disbarred from practice, or ineligible for practice, before the Internal Revenue Service;
•
I am subject to regulations contained in Circular 230 (31 CFR, Subtitle A, Part 10), as amended, governing practice before the Internal Revenue Service;
•
I am authorized to represent the taxpayer identified in Part I for the matter(s) specified there; and
•
I am one of the following:
a
Attorney—a member in good standing of the bar of the highest court of the jurisdiction shown below.
b
Certified Public Accountant—a holder of an active license to practice as a certified public accountant in the jurisdiction shown below.
c
Enrolled Agent—enrolled as an agent by the Internal Revenue Service per the requirements of Circular 230.
d
Officer—a bona fide officer of the taxpayer organization.
e
Full-Time Employee—a full-time employee of the taxpayer.
f
Family Member—a member of the taxpayer’s immediate family (spouse, parent, child, grandparent, grandchild, step-parent, step-child, brother, or sister).
g
Enrolled Actuary—enrolled as an actuary by the Joint Board for the Enrollment of Actuaries under 29 U.S.C. 1242 (the authority to practice before
the Internal Revenue Service is limited by section 10.3(d) of Circular 230).
h
Unenrolled Return Preparer—Authority to practice before the IRS is limited. An unenrolled return preparer may represent, provided the preparer (1)
prepared and signed the return or claim for refund (or prepared if there is no signature space on the form); (2) was eligible to sign the return or
claim for refund; (3) has a valid PTIN; and (4) possesses the required Annual Filing Season Program Record of Completion(s). See Special Rules
and Requirements for Unenrolled Return Preparers in the instructions for additional information.
k Qualifying Student—receives permission to represent taxpayers before the IRS by virtue of his/her status as a law, business, or accounting student
working in an LITC or STCP. See instructions for Part II for additional information and requirements.
r Enrolled Retirement Plan Agent—enrolled as a retirement plan agent under the requirements of Circular 230 (the authority to practice before the
Internal Revenue Service is limited by section 10.3(e)).
IF THIS DECLARATION OF REPRESENTATIVE IS NOT COMPLETED, SIGNED, AND DATED, THE IRS WILL RETURN THE
